 The author demonstrates how the early history of the zoo illuminates three important aspects of the history of nineteenth-century Britain: the politics of culture and leisure in a new public domain which included museums and art galleries; the professionalisation and popularisation of science in a consumer society; and the meanings of the animal world for a growing urban population. Weaving these threads altogether, hepresents a flexible frame of analysis to explain how the zoo was established, how it pursued its policies of animal collection, and how it responded to changing social conditions. Dr Takashi Ito is Associate Professor in Modern British History, Tokyo University of Foreign Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLondon Zoo (London, England) -- History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  a1828-1859.  aBritish culture.  aBritish society.  aCharles Darwin.  aIndian shipbuilders.  aLondon Zoo.  aVictorian London.  aVictorian era.  aVictorians.  aattractions.  acultural life.  aenvironment.  anature exploration.  anature.  asocial life.  aurban population.  aurban promenaders.1 aIto, Takashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204261740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782042617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782042617/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles